{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4af2a611-fd52-4c20-b8b7-5063a56df0d9","content":"The project directory doesn't exist here, but here's exactly what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a **dotnet tool**:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName> <!-- CLI command name -->\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/repo</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n- **`PackAsTool`** — marks the package as a global/local dotnet tool.\n- **`ToolCommandName`** — the command users will type (e.g., `dotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer` then run `my-mcp-server`).\n- **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — tools must be console apps.\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\nNo other special configuration is needed for stdio transport — it just reads stdin/writes stdout, which works naturally as a dotnet tool.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2f115839-aa25-4117-834a-49258329ca04","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory doesn't exist. The user is asking a general question about what they need to configure to publish a C# MCP server as a dotnet tool. I should give them guidance without needing to see files.","outputTokens":536,"requestId":"F3C6:129291:1E9AE08:22E89AA:69F54E66"},"id":"81b4c3a0-3461-4734